112
00:14:49,880 --> 00:14:50,880
Betty?

113
00:14:53,080 --> 00:14:54,400
Oh God.

114
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:15,560
What are you doing?

115
00:15:16,920 --> 00:15:18,560
I'm sorry, my little flower.

116
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:22,000
First,
you have to do what you have to do.

117
00:15:22,840 --> 00:15:24,160
And then...

118
00:15:25,440 --> 00:15:27,400
...you can do what you want to do.

119
00:15:48,520 --> 00:15:50,680
-Yes?
-This is Bellman.

120
00:15:50,760 --> 00:15:53,360
There's been an accident at the studio.

121
00:15:53,920 --> 00:15:56,560
-What kind of accident?
-I, I, I...

122
00:15:56,920 --> 00:15:59,120
Stop the stammering, Bellman, talk.

123
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:00,760
Betty Winter is dead.

124
00:16:02,640 --> 00:16:03,680
I'm coming.

125
00:16:40,120 --> 00:16:41,880
-Oh, I'm sorry.
-I'm sorry.

126
00:16:43,600 --> 00:16:44,600
Hello.

127
00:16:45,040 --> 00:16:46,160
Hi.

128
00:16:46,880 --> 00:16:50,320
You'll have to hurry if you want
to read all these before your exam.

129
00:16:50,400 --> 00:16:52,840
No, I'm just returning them
to the library.

130
00:16:53,240 --> 00:16:54,320
May I?

131
00:16:57,360 --> 00:16:59,200
-What's the exam?
-Forensics.

132
00:16:59,280 --> 00:17:01,440
With Ulrich from the records department
and Gennat.

133
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:05,320
30 minutes with practical part, crime
scene analysis and securing of evidence.

134
00:17:05,400 --> 00:17:07,240
Not exactly my strengths, I fear.

135
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:09,040
You can do this.

136
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:12,600
-You think?
-Why yes, of course.

137
00:17:18,040 --> 00:17:20,200
Did you go to prison this morning?

138
00:17:21,520 --> 00:17:23,640
Yup. Greta doesn't want to see me.

139
00:17:23,720 --> 00:17:25,720
She expressedly put that on record.

140
00:17:27,320 --> 00:17:29,560
-The judgement is still out.
-I have to go.

141
00:17:30,960 --> 00:17:32,160
Break a leg!

142
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:34,280
I didn't mean it like that.

143
00:17:36,680 --> 00:17:37,680
Hi, boss.

144
00:17:38,440 --> 00:17:41,400
-What's up?
-Stay there, we have to go downstairs.

145
00:17:41,480 --> 00:17:44,160
-Where to?
-Babelsberg film studios.

146
00:17:44,240 --> 00:17:46,520
Buddha's order,
we're to go there immediately.

147
00:17:49,240 --> 00:17:50,440
Betty Winter.

148
00:17:50,520 --> 00:17:53,520
One of the greatest, what am I saying,
the greatest hope

149
00:17:53,600 --> 00:17:55,120
we have on stage and in film.

150
00:17:55,200 --> 00:17:56,360
-Had.
-Pardon?

151
00:17:56,440 --> 00:17:57,960
Well, now she's...

152
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:00,160
This is a huge tragedy.

153
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:03,120
And I only just met her.

154
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:05,960
-You mean personally?
-Less than a fortnight ago.

155
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:08,560
An autograph session in Babelsberg,

156
00:18:08,640 --> 00:18:11,040
on Betty's birthday.

157
00:18:13,080 --> 00:18:15,560
Studio shoot for her last film.

158
00:18:16,680 --> 00:18:18,720
Demon of Passion.

159
00:18:18,800 --> 00:18:21,040
-Doesn't that already exist?
-Only on stage.

160
00:18:21,120 --> 00:18:24,120
But now a brandnew musical film,
with sound.

161
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:26,440
So you hear them talk, at the cinema?

162
00:18:26,520 --> 00:18:28,200
Yes, and not just talk. They also sing.

163
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:29,960
Incredible woman.

164
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:32,800
No wonder the Americans
wanted to lure her there.

165
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:34,600
Who was that again?

166
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:36,200
Her husband, Tristan Rot.

167
00:18:36,280 --> 00:18:38,120
He plays the male lead in the film.

168
00:18:38,200 --> 00:18:40,440
Her husband? I thought he was queer.

169
00:18:41,040 --> 00:18:43,240
Yes, he is, but he loved her.

170
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:45,200
Very much.

171
00:18:51,360 --> 00:18:52,920
What's going on here?

172
00:18:53,280 --> 00:18:55,240
Once again, the press was faster than us.

173
00:18:55,320 --> 00:18:57,320
Detective, what's going on here?

174
00:18:57,400 --> 00:18:59,520
Do you know more
about the Betty Winter case?

175
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:01,680
CID, make way.

176
00:19:01,760 --> 00:19:04,920
-No recordings.
-Article 118 of the Reich law:

177
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:07,960
-Every citizen has the right...
-But not now and not here.

178
00:19:08,040 --> 00:19:10,320
-There is no censorship.
-That's enough.

179
00:19:10,400 --> 00:19:12,960
Reinhold,
can't you do something? Please.

180
00:19:13,040 --> 00:19:14,120
Close the gates.

181
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:20,680
Don't touch anything.

182
00:19:30,800 --> 00:19:33,400
-Homicide division, hello.
-Homicide?

183
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:35,880
But it was an accident.

184
00:19:36,760 --> 00:19:39,960
-Who are you?
-Jo Bellman, I'm the producer.

185
00:19:40,560 --> 00:19:42,960
It was obviously an accident.

186
00:19:43,960 --> 00:19:45,440
I mean, we all saw it...

187
00:19:45,520 --> 00:19:47,040
We're here to clarify this.

188
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:50,560
You stay with me.
Everyone else please wait off the set.

189
00:20:06,720 --> 00:20:10,040
So, what exactly happened?

190
00:20:10,720 --> 00:20:13,640
Case study no. 16. A lifeless body,

191
00:20:13,720 --> 00:20:17,160
found in the early morning
by the family gardener

192
00:20:17,240 --> 00:20:20,800
in the property's garage,
identified by the wife,

193
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:22,880
who called the police immediately.

194
00:20:23,360 --> 00:20:26,160
All external circumstances
point towards suicide.

195
00:20:30,280 --> 00:20:31,400
Miss...

196
00:20:31,600 --> 00:20:35,720
-Ritter. Charlotte Ritter.
-Please, Miss Ritter. Ladies first.

197
00:20:39,800 --> 00:20:40,800
What?

198
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:44,520
Explain the five steps of the procedure
to determine death,

199
00:20:44,600 --> 00:20:45,920
Gennat method.

200
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:50,960
One, I get a first general overview
of the crime scene.

201
00:20:54,080 --> 00:20:56,280
-Here?
-Exactly here.

202
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:58,000
Please don't touch.

203
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:13,080
Two, staff will look for evidence
and clues.

204
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:15,440
-How could this have happened?
-The lamp toppled

205
00:21:15,520 --> 00:21:17,280
and the screw heads were torn out.

206
00:21:17,360 --> 00:21:19,240
Where's the cable for the spotlight?

207
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:22,080
-It's here.
-Don't touch!

208
00:21:22,560 --> 00:21:24,720
It's quite the weight, 10kW.

209
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:26,520
Boss, shall we start?

210
00:21:26,600 --> 00:21:30,200
-Search the set for clues. Gennat method.
-Yes, sir.

211
00:21:30,800 --> 00:21:31,800
Gloves!

212
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:36,320
Very good, the gloves.

213
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:48,640
Each detail is tagged.

214
00:21:57,160 --> 00:21:59,840
The spotlight
was fixed with these screws.

215
00:21:59,920 --> 00:22:01,240
Completely intact.

216
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:03,600
Three, take pictures of the crime scene.

217
00:22:07,320 --> 00:22:10,280
Four, witnesses are questioned.

218
00:22:10,360 --> 00:22:12,440
My husband was with me all night.

219
00:22:12,840 --> 00:22:16,000
One moment, Mrs Klopsch.
First the question, then the answer.

220
00:22:16,840 --> 00:22:18,280
-Sorry.
-What's your name?

221
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:20,000
Tilly Brooks.

222
00:22:20,080 --> 00:22:21,680
I see. Where are you from?

223
00:22:22,400 --> 00:22:24,480
-Boston.
-Boston?

224
00:22:24,560 --> 00:22:26,200
Can you tell me in more detail?

225
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:28,800
I didn't see anything,
I was looking the other way.

226
00:22:28,880 --> 00:22:32,440
-What about the husband, Tristan Rot?
-Tristan?

227
00:22:33,480 --> 00:22:35,880
I didn't see anything,
I was up on the rope.

228
00:22:35,960 --> 00:22:39,200
-Rot wasn't here today.
-It was his day off, as far as I know.

229
00:22:39,280 --> 00:22:41,120
Who's responsible for the lighting?

230
00:22:41,200 --> 00:22:42,800
Peter Glaser, the gaffer.

231
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:43,880
Where is he?

232
00:22:43,960 --> 00:22:48,040
He only oversaw the set up. Then they
changed shift and he left with the others.

233
00:22:48,120 --> 00:22:50,120
Do you have his data on file?

234
00:22:50,200 --> 00:22:52,920
-Of course.
-Where do you suspect fingerprints?

235
00:22:54,120 --> 00:22:56,640
-Up there, on the balustrade.
-Correct. Take your time.

236
00:22:56,720 --> 00:22:59,680
On the door handle,
on the steering wheel...

237
00:23:03,040 --> 00:23:04,040
Keep going.

238
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:12,120
-And on the hose on the exhaust pipe.
-Very good.

239
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:15,920
Detective, the incident was filmed
by this camera.

240
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,720
We need to have it developed
immediately.

241
00:23:17,800 --> 00:23:19,680
I ventured to have that arranged.

242
00:23:19,760 --> 00:23:20,920
Here you are.

243
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:22,520
Peter Glaser's personal file.

244
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:24,760
Very well. That's it from us now.

245
00:23:24,840 --> 00:23:25,880
Mr Bellman.

246
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:35,920
The fifth and last step,

247
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:40,400
evacuation of the body and evaluation
of the results at headquarters.

248
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:43,360
Very good, Miss Ritter. Thank you. Next.

249
00:23:43,440 --> 00:23:44,520
Detective!

250
00:23:47,720 --> 00:23:50,880
We need you to sign
that it was an accident. Here.

251
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:53,960
You'll get it
once we've evaluated everything.

252
00:23:54,040 --> 00:23:55,840
And if it was an accident.

253
00:24:06,040 --> 00:24:08,600
In the lab,
the dactyloscopic examination showed

254
00:24:08,680 --> 00:24:12,600
that the deceased's fingerprints
are not congruent with those

255
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:15,120
found on the hose on the exhaust pipe.

256
00:24:15,200 --> 00:24:18,040
A comparison with the wife's fingerprints,

257
00:24:18,120 --> 00:24:19,400
seen on the right here,

258
00:24:19,480 --> 00:24:22,600
confirm the assumption
that this was no suicide,

259
00:24:22,680 --> 00:24:25,720
this was an insidious murder
by the wife.

260
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:27,480
Thank you.

261
00:24:28,120 --> 00:24:29,680
And the motive?

262
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:34,160
-Revenge.
-Really?

